The groundbreaking proposal was put forward by India and South Africa, co-sponsored by Kenya, before the Trips Council of the World Trade Organization (WTO).
The suggestions propose that no WTO member will issue or enforce patent protections on vaccines, drugs, technology or equipment needed to combat Covid-19 for the duration of the pandemic.





Without patent restrictions to protect pharmaceutical profits, it may be possible – and affordable – for low-income countries to produce vaccines and treatment for their people.
Pharmaceutical industries
Sadly, rich countries with strong pharmaceutical industries are not supporting this move. They claim that without patents, the incentives to develop new drugs, treatments and vaccines will disappear.
 Others point to measures they claim will allow low-income countries access to the vaccine. But they fail to admit that none of these measures go far enough to ensure the low-income countries equal access to their share of future vaccines or drugs against Covid-19.
The proposal from India and South Africa, however, would have real impact. India has not been called “the pharmacy to the world” for no reason.
They have both the capacity and the technology to be able to mass-produce complex biological drugs. Patent laws are not laws of nature. They are contracts between states and industries. People have designed them – and people can reform them.



