Pharmaceutical monopolies
In Kenya, and in many countries across East Africa, we know first-hand the cost of pharmaceutical monopolies. Twenty years ago, MSF was the first organisation to bring ARVs to a public health facility in Kenya.
The move followed a global campaign to bring down drug prices through generic production, launched when we were struggling to assist HIV patients who were left to die whilst people in rich countries had access to ARVs.
Globally, millions of people lost their lives before the battle was over, but in the end HIV drugs eventually became available because of the defeat of the pharmaceutical monopolies.
Today we are calling on countries to listen to the experience of the HIV/Aids epidemic and come together to support this bold patent waiver proposal.
Countries across East Africa should share their experience and ask their international partners – those in countires that are not supporting this gamechanging move – to support this proposal. We should support initiatives that will empower countries to be able to face future crises without being at the mercy of aid.





Now is the time to raise our voices to support a proposal that represents a real chance for people whose lives are threatened by a pandemic we face a long struggle to defeat.



